## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET 5+ — it's completely removed, not just deprecated.
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also throws** — the entire cooperative abort model is gone.
3. **`default(T)` for non-nullable reference types** — now triggers nullable warnings.

### Why `Thread.Abort()` Was Removed

It was inherently unsafe — it could corrupt state by interrupting code mid-execution (inside `finally` blocks, during `lock` releases, etc.). .NET Core/5+ enforces **cooperative cancellation** via `CancellationToken`.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes work with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work delegate receives a CancellationToken it MUST observe.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            // Task.Run uses the ThreadPool instead of raw threads —
            // more efficient and the standard pattern in modern .NET.
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            task.Wait(cts.Token);
            return task.Result;
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            // Unwrap single-exception aggregates for cleaner call-site handling.
            if (ex.InnerException is OperationCanceledException
                && cts.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                throw new TimeoutException(
                    $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
            }

            throw ex.InnerException!;
        }
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Async version — preferred in modern .NET code.
    /// </summary>
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Usage Comparison

```csharp
// ── OLD (.NET Framework) ──
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => SlowDatabaseCall(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// ── NEW (.NET 8) — sync ──
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct => SlowDatabaseCall(ct),   // pass token into the work
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// ── NEW (.NET 8) — async (preferred) ──
var result = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(
    async ct => await SlowDatabaseCallAsync(ct),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Work must observe the token** | Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, cancellation is *cooperative*. If your work ignores the `CancellationToken`, it keeps running after timeout — you only stop *waiting*. |
| **Fire-and-forget leak** | If work doesn't check `ct.IsCancellationRequested` or pass `ct` to I/O calls, the background task becomes orphaned. |
| **`Task.Result` vs `await`** | The sync version uses `.Wait()` / `.Result` which can deadlock in UI/ASP.NET contexts with a `SynchronizationContext`. Prefer the async version. |
| **Exception wrapping changed** | `Task.Run` wraps exceptions in `AggregateException`; the migrated code unwraps single exceptions, but test your catch sites. |
| **`WaitAsync` is .NET 6+** | The `Task.WaitAsync(CancellationToken)` API didn't exist in earlier .NET Core — it's fine for .NET 8. |

### If You Truly Can't Make Work Cooperative

As a last resort, you can run work in a **separate process** and kill it — but this is heavy. There is no safe in-process forced termination in .NET 8.
